When a pigment absorbs light energy, one of three things will occur: Energy may be dissipated as heat; it may be re-emitted immediately as a longer wavelength, a phenomenon known as fluorescence; or the energy may trigger a chemical reaction, as in photosynthesis. In plant photosynthesis, the action begins at the PSII chlorophyll–protein complex which becomes excited and loses an electron; this electron is passed through a series of enzymes until it is transferred to water, ­causing it to lose electrons:
